value.value: A blood vessel arising from the brachial artery in the center of the upper arm that supplies blood to the triceps muscle and humerus.

One of the extraoculomotor muscles, which arises from a common tendinous ring in the posterior portion of the orbit, inserts on the upper part of the sclera, is innervated by CN III, and functions to elevate, adduct, and medially rotate the eye.
One of the three semicircular canals found in the osseous labyrinth of the inner ear, which detects rotation of the head around a rostral-caudal (anterior-posterior) axis.

A discrete space situated dorsal to the midbrain where the arachnoid mater and pia mater are separated, and through which a number of important vascular structures pass, including the great cerebral vein, the basal vein of Rosenthal, and the posterior cerebral artery.
The superior aspect of the liver.
A gyrus or ridge on the outer surface of the temporal lobe between the horizontal portion of the fissure of Sylvius and the superior temporal sulcus.
A 17-alkylated orally active androgenic steroid. Calusterone may alter the metabolism of estradiol and reduce estrogen production. (NCI04)

A non-neoplastic growth in the vocal cord. It is characterized by tissue swelling in both vocal cords in a symmetrical manner. It is caused by vocal abuse behavior. Hoarseness is the presenting symptom.
A groove or cleft that divides the outer surface of the temporal lobe running parallel to the horizontal portion of the fissure of Sylvius.
An artery arising from the axillary artery that supplies the muscles of the superior chest.
The site of the opening (non-valve) at which the superior vena cava enters the right atrium.

The smallest of the four vestibular nuclei located dorsally and rostrally in the vestibular complex and limited to the caudal pons, where it is situated in the wall of the 4th ventricle in the brain; it is involved in vestibuloocular reflex pathways.

label.value: Supporting Cell of the Nervous System

value.value: A cell that serves to provide support and protection and perhaps contribute to the nutrition of principal or other cells of the nervous system.
The inner aspect of the sclera, located adjacent to the choroid. It contains thin collagen fibers and elastic fibers, fibroblasts, melanocytes, macrophages, and other connective tissue cells.
A convolution located on the anterior part of the inferior parietal lobe of the brain. In the dominant hemisphere, it plays a role in the comprehension of written language.
A superficial vein that ascends the forehead and joins with the frontal vein to form the angular vein.
An artery located in the abdomen that provides blood to the adrenal glands.

One of four rotator cuff muscles that form a musculotendinous cuff around the glenohumeral joint, which provides muscular support to the shoulder. It arises from the supraspinous fossa of the scapula, inserts into the greater tubercle of the humerus, and assists to abduct the arm.
Any deviation from the normal structure or function of the skin or subcutaneous tissue that is manifested by a characteristic set of symptoms and signs.
A subarachnoid cistern that is located superior to the tentorium cerebelli in the brain.
The small coiled tubes in the skin that produce and secrete sweat.
The small tube that drains sweat from the sweat gland to the skin.

A cerebrospinal fluid-filled subarachnoid space extending into the Sylvian fissure that separates the temporal lobe from both the frontal and the parietal lobes; it contains the middle cerebral artery and some of its branches.
The space between the presynaptic terminal and the postsynaptic membrane.
Immovable articulation by close union, as in sutures.

A membrane-lined sac that is located in a joint, and is filled with synovial fluid; it provides a cushion between bones and tendons and/or muscles, decreasing the friction between two moving structures and allowing for unrestricted movement.
A viscid fluid secreted by the synovial membrane, serving as a lubricant.
Any vein within the general circulation that transports blood back to the right atrium of the heart.
A benign, intermediate, or malignant neoplasm involving the skin.
The first thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The tenth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The eleventh thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The twelfth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The second thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The third thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The fourth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The fifth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The sixth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The seventh thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
A benign or malignant round or oval and elevated solid lesion that arises from the skin or subcutaneous tissue.
The eighth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The ninth thoracic vertebra counting from the top down.
The lower part of the epididymis.
The part of the sperm called the flagellum; it functions to propel the sperm towards the egg.
An artery arising from the dorsalis pedis artery at the navicular bone that supplies the articulations of the tarsus and the extensor brevis digitorum muscle.
The synovial joints between the tarsal bones of the foot.
A dense fibrous tissue layer located in the eyelid, which gives the lids shape, strength, and a place for muscles to attach. It contains numerous Meibomian glands.
Any one of the seven bones forming the instep of the foot.
The opening at the apex of the taste bud.
